Project Report: Ukuqala Frontend Development
1. Executive Summary
The frontend of the Ukuqala platform has been engineered as a high-performance, responsive React application. It serves as the primary interface for healthcare practitioners to manage patient records and monitor vital signs in real-time. The system is now successfully integrated with the Version 4 RESTful API, ensuring secure data persistence and role-based access.

2. Core Modules & Functionality
2.1 Authentication & Security (Requirement 4.1)
Implementation: Developed a secure entry point via /login and /register routes.

Session Management: Implemented JWT (JSON Web Token) handling. Upon successful authentication, the token is stored in localStorage to maintain user sessions across page refreshes.

Route Protection: Developed a guard mechanism that redirects unauthenticated users to the login page if they attempt to access protected dashboards.

2.2 Patient Management (Requirement 4.3)
Dynamic Listing: A centralized dashboard displays a comprehensive table of patients fetched from the GET /api/v4/patients endpoint.

Profile Views: Individualized patient profile pages (e.g., Kate’s Profile) provide a deep dive into patient conditions and historical data.

CRUD Logic: Full integration for adding new patients, updating existing records, and a deletion flow with a confirmation safety check.

2.3 Health Vitals Tracking (Requirement 4.4)
Nested Data Architecture: The system utilizes nested routing (/patients/:id/vitals) to keep health data strictly associated with the correct patient.

Clinical Metrics: Support for recording Heart Rate (bpm), Blood Pressure (mmHg), and Temperature (°C).

Chronological History: A specialized "Vitals History" component displays data in reverse chronological order, allowing practitioners to see the most recent health trends immediately.

3. Technical Architecture
3.1 API Client & Middleware (Requirement 5)
Environment-Driven Config: The application uses a centralized apiClient.js utilizing import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL to prevent hardcoded endpoints.

Request Interceptor: Automatically injects the Authorization: Bearer <token> header into every outgoing request to satisfy backend security requirements.

Response Interceptor (Requirement 5.4): A global error handler that detects 401 Unauthorized responses, clears local session data, and redirects the user to login, preventing security leaks.

3.2 UI/UX Enhancements (Requirement 3 - Bonus)
Async Feedback: Replaced static loading text with a CSS-animated spinner for a professional feel during data fetching.

Safety Prompts: Implemented a logout confirmation modal to prevent accidental session termination.

Responsive Layout: Applied Flexbox and media queries to ensure the dashboard and patient profiles are accessible on tablets and mobile devices used in clinical environments.
